  "buggy_functions": ["azx_init_chip"],
  "confidence": 0.95,
  "reasoning": "The bug occurs because azx_init_chip() skips initialization of the CORB/RIRB (Command/Response ring buffers) when chip->single_cmd is set, even during a full reset (full_reset=1). When the system suspends and resumes: (1) During suspend, azx_stop_chip() sets chip->initialized=0 but does NOT reset the error recovery flags (polling_mode, single_cmd, poll_count). (2) During resume, azx_init_chip(chip, 1) is called for full reset. (3) However, because single_cmd flag was left at 1 from a previous timeout error, the CORB/RIRB initialization in azx_init_cmd_io() is skipped (line 1222-1223: 'if (!chip->single_cmd) azx_init_cmd_io(chip)'). (4) This leaves the CORB/RIRB uninitialized after resume, causing codec communication failures. The fix: When full_reset=1 (indicating full hardware reset during suspend/resume or bus reset), the CORB/RIRB should ALWAYS be initialized regardless of the single_cmd flag. The condition on line 1222 should be changed from 'if (!chip->single_cmd)' to 'if (!chip->single_cmd || full_reset)' to ensure proper re-initialization after suspend/resume."
}

